</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Yes, these should be fantasy races that should be OK and are not &quot;property&quot; of some company currently. <br>
<br>
Elves, dwarves, dragons, giants, ogres, trolls -- many of these have been in mythical existence since ancient times, or Medieval Europe, or Scandinavian mythology. No person today has a sole copyright on them.<br>
<br>
Orcs -- I could be wrong, but I think JRR Tolkien invented Orcs. I have never heard of &quot;orcs&quot; before in ANY world literature before the writings of Tolkien in the early 20th Century.  However, I doubt that Tolkien legally retained a sole copyright on Orcs.... just look at the 5 bazillion fantasy games that use them today. Conclusion? The use of the mythical Orcs probably belongs to the public domain by now. <br>
<br>
Also, there is a clause in international copyright rules. If the original author dies, after some time has passed.... there are certain elements that can automatically go into the public domain.  <br>
<br>
Barbarians -- definitely public domain. Ancient Greeks first coined the term &quot;barbarian&quot; to refer to uncivilized savages who spoke a garbled language that sounded like &quot;ber ber ber ber&quot; <br>
<br>
The best way to distinguish yourself is to give names and culture to each of your races. For example, dont just call them elves. Call them something like &quot;The elven people called the Seldarain who dwell in the forest of blah blah blah....&quot;  And think of making them different from the other elves. Give them a couple of features or traits that totally makes them stand out from the typical elves in D&amp;D or Everquest. Make your elves unique! More people will want to read your stories if your creatures are unique and really stand out. <br>
<br>
Likewise, don't just call them Giants.  Write about them like &quot;And there lived beyond the Great Glacier a large race of giant men, who refer to themselves as the Jarls of Kranigsheim&quot; <br>
<br>
